Fix a real, TSan-reproducible data race in WAMR's own thread manager:
wasm_exec_env_destroy() removes itself from its cluster's exec_env list
without taking cluster->lock, on the assumption that being the cluster's
last live thread makes that safe — an assumption wasm_set_exception()'s
global wasm_clusters_search_exec_env() lookup (triggered by *any* wasm
exception anywhere, including our own kill()/wasm_runtime_terminate())
violates by locking every live cluster while scanning, including one
mid-teardown elsewhere. See pymergetic/metal's scripts/verify-linux-
threads.sh (tests/thread_stress_test.c) for the reproduction, and this same
tree's docs/SOURCETREE.md "Vendoring" for how/why this patch exists.
Applied by scripts/setup-wamr.sh.

diff --git a/core/iwasm/libraries/thread-mgr/thread_manager.c b/core/iwasm/libraries/thread-mgr/thread_manager.c
index 8f3a6317..ee9c6912 100644
--- a/core/iwasm/libraries/thread-mgr/thread_manager.c
+++ b/core/iwasm/libraries/thread-mgr/thread_manager.c
@@ -440,11 +440,41 @@ wasm_cluster_del_exec_env_internal(WASMCluster *cluster, WASMExecEnv *exec_env,
     return ret;
 }
 
-/* The caller should lock cluster->lock for thread safety */
+/*
+ * pymergetic/metal vendor patch (patches/wamr/0002-thread-mgr-exec-env-destroy-lock.patch):
+ * this used to be "return wasm_cluster_del_exec_env_internal(cluster,
+ * exec_env, true)" with no lock at all, on the strength of this
+ * function's *only* caller (wasm_exec_env_destroy()) reasoning that
+ * being the cluster's last live thread makes cluster->lock unnecessary.
+ * That reasoning doesn't hold against wasm_clusters_search_exec_env()
+ * (wasm_set_exception()'s own lookup, walking *every* live cluster,
+ * including one mid-teardown on another thread, whenever *any* wasm
+ * code anywhere raises an exception) — under ThreadSanitizer this is a
+ * real, reproducible data race the moment more than one module instance
+ * can be running/tearing down concurrently, which is the normal case
+ * for a long-lived multi-module host. Locking here instead (matching
+ * every *other* bh_list_remove(&cluster->exec_env_list) caller in this
+ * file, e.g. wasm_cluster_wait_for_all_except_self() a few lines above)
+ * closes it. can_destroy_cluster=false + destroying below, once
+ * unlocked, avoids the alternative bug that risks: calling
+ * os_mutex_destroy() on a mutex this same thread still holds (which is
+ * exactly what wasm_cluster_destroy() does to cluster->lock itself).
+ */
 bool
 wasm_cluster_del_exec_env(WASMCluster *cluster, WASMExecEnv *exec_env)
 {
-    return wasm_cluster_del_exec_env_internal(cluster, exec_env, true);
+    bool ret, now_empty;
+
+    os_mutex_lock(&cluster->lock);
+    ret = wasm_cluster_del_exec_env_internal(cluster, exec_env, false);
+    now_empty = (cluster->exec_env_list.len == 0);
+    os_mutex_unlock(&cluster->lock);
+
+    if (now_empty) {
+        wasm_cluster_destroy(cluster);
+    }
+
+    return ret;
 }
 
 static WASMExecEnv *
